    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-05T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-05T13:00:00-05:00" n="1227"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1227">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 367.116/248</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgenthau</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-05T20:00:00+02:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">December 5, 1914, 8 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 11, 430 p. m]</hi>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>123. Had a long interview with Minister of the Interior and Minister of Public
                    Instruction. They offered to treat American institutions the same as foreign
                    institutions are treated in the United States and to delay enforcement of most
                    of the objectionable instructions sixty days.<note n="1" xml:id="d1227fn1">The
                        instructions to provincial officials concerning private religious,
                        educational and benevolent institutions, schools and medical institutions,
                        transmitted by the Ambassador with his despatch No 142, December 5, 1914
                        (File No. 367.116/273), are printed in <ref target="frus1916#pg_972">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, pp. 972</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1916#pg_4">4</ref>.</note> They state that they principally
                    desire to obtain supervisory control of and direct relations with foreign
                    institutions without the guardianship of the Embassy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
